UNDIAGNOSED DISEASE, PORCINE - CHINA (07): REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
******************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
[1]
Date: Wed 30 May 2007
Source: Shanghai Daily [edited]
<http://www.shanghaidaily.com/article/?id=317777>

China is making a count of the number of pigs dead from blue ear
disease and will publish the figure soon, a senior official with the
country's Ministry of Agriculture said today [30 May 2007].
"It's true that China has blue ear disease, but it's not true, as
some foreign media have reported, that the disease has killed 20
million pigs," Li Jinxiang, vice director general with Veterinary
Bureau of the ministry, told China Business News yesterday [29 May
2007]. "These reports are groundless," Li said. [On 29 May 2007,] the
Financial Times linked China's recent pork price hike with the
outbreak of blue ear disease, also known as porcine reproductive and
respiratory syndrome [PRRS]. It also said that many pigs had died
from foot-and-mouth disease [FMD], which was another cause of the
price hike. "However, the report provided no evidence except some
guess-work figures from a so-called 'insider'," Li told the newspaper.
The disease may lead to dead fetuses or abortion, and piglets have
almost no resistance to the disease. The mortality for infected
piglets is 50 percent.
[In 2006,] an outbreak of blue ear disease was one of the causes of a
short supply of live pigs, a statement by the State Council said [on
20 May 2007.]
According to the Ministry of Agriculture, in April [2007], live pigs
nationwide were priced 71.3 percent higher than a year earlier
[2006], and pork, 35.5 percent higher, largely due to tightened supply.
[On Mon 28 May 2007,] Chinese Premier, Wen Jiabao, asked local
governments at all levels to ensure the supply of pork and maintain
market order amid rising concerns over the soaring price of pork.
The disease is under control, Li said. Pork prices in northern
China's Liaoning and Jilin provinces have seen some drops.
[Byline: Alice Gu]
--
Communicated by:
FMD News
FMD Surveillance and Modeling Laboratory
